criticalNotes: Both the 'Gulf Island soft coral' and the 'Race Rocks/Browning Passage/Weynton Passage soft coral' are in the genus Alcyonium. However, they are genetically different and have not yet been circumscribed.

Multiple Euphysa species are likely present in the region. "Differences are apparently in the young specimens, but generally we only ever see the adults. Euphysa japonica has four tentacles, all alike, including in the youngest stages. Euphysa flammea has four alike tentacles as an adult, but they develop successively, and it is released with only one tentacle. Euphysa tentaculata (which may well be an Arctic species) is said to have one long tentacle, two half as long, and one bulb without tentacles. I’ve noticed that I see Euphysa medusae both in the spring and in the fall (rarely if ever in the summer)—these could be two different species.” (Claudia Mills pers. comm., 2020).
This cryptic species was recently separated from Aegina citrea (Lindsay, 2017). "Everything from surface waters in the Salish Sea is Solmudaegina nematophora" (Claudia Mills, pers. comm. 2021)

"Aequorea victoria is our native species, named nearby, whereas A. forskalea is native to Europe or the East Coast. Sarah Abboud's recent molecular analysis of all the Aequorea on the west coast showed they belonged to a 'victoria' clade with many potential species/sub-species within. This is a species complex, though Sarah has not published or renamed anything" (Wyatt Patry, pers. comm. 2020).
Reported as Urticina crassicornis in collections at the RBCM (986-00197-009), a species commonly conflated with U. grebelnyia. See Sanamyan & Sanamyan, 2006

PMLS records list Cadlina luteomarginata complex due to challenges in field identification. However, here we recognize both Cadlina klasmalmbergi and B. luteomarginata based on confirmed observational evidence. "True Cadlina luteomarginata have more conspicuous tubercles and lack yellow glands near the mantle edge. C. klasmalmbergi is more common in BC than C. luteomarginata. Note that there are 201 obs of C. luteomarginata in PMLS and none of C. klasmalmbergi" (Karin Fletcher, pers. comm 2021).

There is a California form as originally described from Monterey, California (Apata pricei) and another form collected in California (Apata pricei pricei) and a Western Pacific form (Apata pricei komandorica) but no specimens from the Salish Sea have been sequenced to know if we have either the second California form or the Western Pacific form or both. We do not have the form as originally described in MacFarland, 1966.
The native Mytilus trossulus cannot be discriminated from the non-native M. edulis / M. galloprovincialis in the field.

Triopha modesta is recognized as a trans-Pacific species, and is most likely to occur off the coast of British Columbia. Triopha catalinae has been determined to be an eastern Pacific species (but there is overlap). See Gosliner et al. 2020

"Tonicella undocaerulea is restricted to the Sea of Japan (maybe Sea of Okhotsk too) region. The species that we have identified as T. undocearulea in the eastern Pacific is in fact an undescribed species. Doug Eernisse and I are going to describe this species. I believe that Doug has done some barcoding on both" (Roger Clark, pers. comm. 2020).
RBCM records report this specimen under the name of Chlamys islandica—an erroneous application of an Atlantic species concept.
Reported as Lyonsia californica Conrad, 1837 (RBCM 979-03305). The original ID by Cowan is Lyonsia pugetensis which is now accepted as Lyonsia bracteata.

McTaggart Cowan reports Diplodonta orbella (Gould, 1851) = Zemysina orbella (Gould, 1851). However, this taxon has since been split, with Zemysina orbella recognized as a southern species and Diplodonta impolita S.S. Berry, 1953 as a northern species (Coan et al. 2000).
Reported as Cyclocardia ventricosa (Gould, 1850), an unaccepted according to WoRMS (2021)

Accessioned in collections at the RBCM as Zelentia pustulata (Alder & Hancock, 1854), which is now recognized as being limited to the Atlantic. Our Pacific species is Zelentia nepunicea Korshunova, Fletcher, Lundin, Picton & Martynov, 2018
Accessioned in RBCM collections under the name Cranopsis cucullata (Gould, 1846), an unaccepted synonym according to WoRMS (2021)
Chaetopterus does occur in the region but which species has not yet been documented

"Myxicola infundibulum"— In Europe M. infundibulum is found in soft-sediments & M. aesthetica is the one hanging from docks & hard-surfaces. If our NEP specimens are really the same as a European species they would be M. infundibulum. However, our NEP specimens are distinctly different both morphologically & genetically from infundibulum. In the past several NEP species of Myxicola were described from California, Puget Sound, & Alaska. All of the original specimens need to be re-examined so we can decide what name (or names) to use in the NEP

Northeast Pacific specimens are likely to be mis-identified as the name is a holdover from when European literature dominated polychaete systematics. This species was described from the Arctic, and is a European species. Northern European specimens have a distinct color pattern similar to our Cheilonereis cyclurus, which is very different from Northeast Pacific worms identified as N. zonata
Epigamia alexandri describes a European species that is most probably not here. What is here is Epigamia magna (Berkeley 1923)

The genus name Pandalus is adopted as per WoRMS (2021), though there is some contention regarding this matter. "Since generic splits are rather arbitrary, I am not sure why they [split off Pandalus lucidirimicolus] when all the Pandalopsis fall out together in their tree" (Gregory Jensen, pers. comm. 2019).
Accessioned in the RBCM collections as Sergestes similis, an unaccepted synonym according to WoRMS (2021).
Species complex currently under revision.
Species complex currently under revision.
Previously misidentified as Strongylocentrotus fragilis Jackson, 1912.

Historically recorded as 'Didemnun/Trididemnum', this report includes encrusting whitish compound tunicates that often form large sheets. It is an impossible task to go further with IDs in the field without collecting samples

notes: Reported as Squalus acanthias in CMN catalogue
